Baseline:  
Sense is that electoral sentiment is still broadly consistent with 2016 election, though voter engagement has decreased; electoral preparations appear broadly on track despite partisan contention and subsequent postponement of electoral rolls revision project. Considerations:
- Parliamentary seat distribution: Of 275 seats, 172 are in districts that the NPP won by 1.75:1 or greater in last election; only 68 seats are in districts that the NDC won by a corresponding amount;
- Polling:  One small poll (extremely low confidence based on small sample size and opaque methodology) puts NPP vote-share broadly in line with 2016.  Larger polls are ambiguous; last round of Afrobarometer sentiment survey (2016-2018) showed relative satisfaction with the (then) new government (by proportion of people answering ‘fairly well’ or better to questions regarding government performance); more recent Afrobarometer polling (results published Dec. 2019) showed a decline in expected voter participation, which could suggest some level of unmet expectation; among declared voters, NPP vote share exceeded NDC vote share;
- Coronavirus response: Press coverage of government response appears largely positive (based on review of limited number of news sources), government thus far appears to have more or less effectively refuted opposition criticism; this could change as economic pain escalates;
- Opposition disarray: severe NDC infighting and expulsion of influential party members this close to a scheduled election bodes ill for prospect of increasing opposition vote share.
